erners chase Dubai's promise of socioeconomic elevation for the few. Through an ethnography informed by postcolonial and feminist theory, Le Renard reveals the diverse experiences and trajectories of white and non-white, male and female Westerners to understand the shifting and contingent nature of Westernness—and also its deep connection to whiteness and heteronormativity. Western Privilege offers a singular look at the lived reality of structural racism in cities of the global South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aForeign workerszUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate)xSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aWhitesxRace identityzUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate) 0aWhitesxRace identityzUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate). 0aWhiteszUnited Arab EmirateszDubayy (Emirate)xSocial conditionsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh  aDubai.  aGender.  aHeteronormativity.  aIntimacy.  aLabor.  aMigration.  aPostcolonial studies.  aWesternness.  aWhiteness.  arace and class.1 aKuntz, Jane.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362924040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503629240423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503629240/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles